{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"605e945d-acdd-481e-8616-caee463a0f77","content":"The template has the required fields (`identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `classifications`, `tags`) but has several gaps before it's publish-ready:\n\n**Must fix:**\n- **No `description`** — NuGet.org and `dotnet new list` will show nothing. Add a `\"description\"` field.\n- **`Framework` symbol missing `replaces`** — Without `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or similar), the chosen framework value won't actually be substituted into your `.csproj` files.\n\n**Strongly recommended:**\n- **No `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"https://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for editor validation.\n- **No `groupIdentity`** — Needed to group template variants on NuGet (e.g. `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n- **No `defaultName`** — Controls the fallback project name (e.g. `\"defaultName\": \"MyWebApi1\"`).\n\n**Summary:** Not ready yet. The missing `description` and the non-functional `Framework` parameter are the biggest issues.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"00b20ae2-a8b9-4f45-abdf-c7977b275118","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields.\n\nIssues I can spot:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required but highly recommended for validation and editor support. The standard schema URL is `https://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet publishing to group related templates.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of the same template exist.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, but good practice.\n\n5. **Missing `defaultName`** — The default project name when none is specified.\n   \nThe core required fields are all there, but I'm noticing the `Framework` symbol lacks a `replaces` property to actually substitute values in the generated files, and there's no `description` field which is critical for NuGet visibility and the `dotnet new list` command.","outputTokens":714},"id":"d8873b70-7f6c-4d54-854f-210600fb3eea","timestamp":"2026-04-09T15:17:02.276Z","parentId":"b13f6621-079a-43ec-83af-53e3bd78c39e"}
